It seems, that you don&#39;t understand a static context.

In the first example, you have your `isKeyDown(int)` method as a class member, meaning, that if you want to call that method, you have to create a new instance of the Input class and call the method on it afterwards.
Example:
```java
public Boolean run() {
  Input input = new Input()
  return input.isKeyDown(GLFW.GLFW_KEY_ESCAPE);
}
```

In the second example, you are trying to access a class member from its&#39;s static context, which is not possible and it makes sense, once you understand `static`.

Your other solution is to make the `Input` class a singleton. That means there&#39;s only one istance of the class in the whole application and then you access the object as a static class from java. You can do that by using the kotlin `object` keyword.
Example:
```kotlin
object Input
{
    private val keyArray: BooleanArray = BooleanArray(GLFW.GLFW_KEY_LAST)

    @JvmStatic
    fun isKeyDown(key: Int): Boolean {
        return keyArray[key]
    }
}
```
and then your java caller method:
```java
public Boolean run() {
  return Input.isKeyDown(GLFW.GLFW_KEY_ESCAPE);
}
```

Based on what I see, the second option is probably the one you want to use.
Here you can read about java `static` modifier: https://www.baeldung.com/java-static

